# Understanding the Comparable Interface
Comparable is an interface and compareTo(Object o) is a method inside Comparable interface
Q1. The Problem: How Do We Sort Custom Objects? 🤔
    Let’s say you're building a library app for your college. You store books with their title and year of publication.
    When users view the book list, you want it to appear in alphabetical order.

    You write the code, store a few books in a list, and try to sort them using Collections.sort().
    But instead of a sorted list, you get an error.

    That’s because Java doesn’t automatically know how to sort your custom Book objects.
    It only knows how to sort basic types like numbers and strings. If you want Java to
    sort your own objects, you have to teach it how to compare them.

    This is where the Comparable interface comes in.

Q2. What Exactly Is the Comparable Interface? 💡
Standard Definition:
    The Comparable interface lets a class define how its objects should be compared with each other. It contains just one method:

        int compareTo(Object o)


Q3. Why Is It So Important? 🎯
    Sorting is everywhere — names, dates, scores, prices. Java provides tools like Collections.sort(),
    but they can only work if the objects know how to compare themselves.

    If you don’t use Comparable, Java won’t know how to sort your list of books, students, or any other custom type.
    You'll either get an error or an unsorted list.

    By implementing Comparable, your class says, “I know how to compare myself to another object,” and
    Java can then handle sorting automatically.

Q4. How It Works: A Practical Example
    Let’s create a Book class and sort a list of books by title.

    1. Without Comparable:
            class Book {
                String title;
                int year;

                Book(String title, int year) {
                    this.title = title;
                    this.year = year;
                }
            }
        Now you try:
            List<Book> books = new ArrayList<>();
            books.add(new Book("C Programming", 2020));
            books.add(new Book("Java Basics", 2018));
            Collections.sort(books); // ❌ Error: Book doesn't implement Comparable

        Java throws an error — it doesn’t know how to compare two Book objects.

    2. With Comparable:
            class Book implements Comparable<Book> {
                String title;
                int year;

                Book(String title, int year) {
                    this.title = title;
                    this.year = year;
                }

                @Override
                public int compareTo(Book other) {
                    return this.title.compareTo(other.title);
                }
            }
        Now when you run:
            Collections.sort(books);

        The books will be sorted by title in A-Z order.

Q5. What Does compareTo() Return?
    The compareTo() method returns:
        1. A negative number if the current object comes before the other
        2. Zero if both are equal
        3. A positive number if the current object comes after the other

    This result tells Java how to arrange the items.

# Key Takeaways 📝:
    1. The Comparable interface is used to define how objects should be sorted.
    2. It contains one method: compareTo(), which compares the current object with another.
    3. If you want your class to be sortable using Collections.sort(), you must implement Comparable.
    4. You can only define one natural order using Comparable (like by name or by score).
    5. For multiple sorting rules, use the Comparator interface.

# Common Questions Asked in Interviews and How to Answer:

    Q1. What is the Comparable interface and why is it used?
    Answer: 1. The Comparable interface is used to define a natural ordering for objects of a class. It allows you to compare objects,
               which is particularly useful when sorting collections like List or Set. By implementing Comparable, you specify how two
               instances of the class should be compared, which simplifies sorting.
            2. You might be asked to explain the purpose of the Comparable interface and how it is used to define natural ordering.

    Q2. How is compareTo() different from equals()?
    Answer: 1. compareTo() is used for sorting objects and returns a value that indicates whether the object is less than,
               equal to, or greater than another. equals() is used to check if two objects are logically the same.
               While compareTo() defines the order, equals() defines equality.
            2. Be prepared to explain the differences and how compareTo() is used for sorting while equals() is used for checking equality.

    Q3. Can you implement multiple sorting orders using Comparable?
    Answer: 1. No, Comparable can only define one natural order. If you need multiple sorting criteria,
               you should use the Comparator interface, which allows you to define multiple sorting
               strategies without changing the original class implementation.
            2. This question often leads into discussing why Comparable is best for a single natural order
               and how the Comparator interface can be used for multiple sorting criteria.

    Q4. What happens if compareTo() is inconsistent with equals()?
    Answer: 1. If compareTo() is inconsistent with equals(), it may lead to unexpected behavior, particularly in
               sorted collections like TreeSet or TreeMap, which rely on compareTo(). Objects considered equal
               by equals() might be treated differently by compareTo(), leading to duplicates or incorrect ordering.
            2. You may be asked to explain the consequences of inconsistency and why maintaining consistency is important,
               especially when using sets or maps.